A Land Use Solution in Search of a Transport Problem

Jonathan Wright @citywright

30 July 2016

High-speed rail has captured Australias imagination for decades, generating studies and attracting support across the political spectrum. Sydney to Melbourne is already the fifth-most traveled commercial air route in the world. With all the hassles of flying, the thought of being whisked comfortably from Spencer Street to Circular Quay in under two hours is indeed alluring. But sky-high construction costs and long profitability timelines have kept the dream out of reach. According to the latest government report, high-speed rail from Brisbane to Melbourne could cost $114 billion and take 40 years to cover costs.

Enter Consolidated Land and Rail Australia (CLARA), a private group with a proposal to deliver the first stage high-speed rail from Sydney to Melbourne without public funding. All this while promising to relieve development pressures and unclog congestion in existing cities by rebalancing settlement to eight new regional cities along the rail line. The proposal relies on value capture, an established and highly-touted model for funding public infrastructure by capitalizing on increased land values through tax or contributions.

But the CLARA proposal bets big on three tenuous assumptions that should give the government pause: the ease of creating new cities, the benefits of urban decentralization, and the long-term viability of high-speed rail.

Value capture works best when supporting sensible infrastructure near existing land use assets, [like Sydneys Central station](https://infrastructure.gov.au/rail/trains/high_speed/files/HSR_Phase_2_Chapter_7.pdf. If it also requires compulsory acquisition, the government must take extra care not to conflate private profits with public interest. CLARA would create and capture value from new cities along the line, the cost and complexity of which cannot be underestimated. New cities need more than housing and a station. They need roads and pipes; infrastructure for energy, waste, and communications; parks, reserves, schools, hospitals, and businesses. And cities needs people to run all of these; not everyone will commune by train.

So cities must also be communities vibrant and attractive places in their own right. Places are successful when they impart a sense of the timeless. The irony of a futuristic, hyper-connected city in a paddock is that it would be wholly disconnected from any sense of history. The CLARA proposal risks putting too much faith in our ability to create sustainable places from scratch. Great thinkers from Jane Jacobs to Jan Gehl have taught that the soul of great places emerge from the unplanned and unexpected.

If these cities fail to take off, how will later stages of the rail be funded? What would be the public cost of propping these cities up, or the consequences of winding them down?

CLARA touts high-speed rail as the best technology available for the foreseeable future. But the transport sector is undergoing a dramatic upheaval from a convergence of disruptive technologies and the rise of the sharing economy. Advances in autonomous vehicles could dramatically increase the safety and capacity of existing motorways, rebalancing the location equation for housing. Advances in virtual and augmented reality could reduce the need for travel altogether. New technologies that sound outlandish now could be closer than we think.

If the rail line fails to achieve the necessary ridership to cover costs, will the public be willing and able to subsidize its operations to keep it running?

Even if we could create livable cities, its worth asking whether we should. Seventy years of outward sprawl has left us struggling to pay maintenance and mortgages. Decades of designing cities for cars and traffic, to paraphrase the urbanist Fred Kent, have embedded social challenges into the fabric of our cities: from traffic congestion to social disconnection. The CLARA proposal mistakenly assumes that the answer to our growing cities is to continue spreading further out, rather than seeking infrastructure efficiency through consolidation.

We cannot afford to disregard the risks of success. If the CLARA proposal were built, what would the opportunity costs be for our existing cities? Which infrastructure projects and public policies would we forgo by shifting money, energy, and expertise towards a high-speed rail line and eight new cities?

Its easy to find risks in big ideas, and the CLARA proposal deserves credit for its ambition. This shouldnt stop governments from thinking big, for the wicked problems facing our cities climate change, housing affordability, aging population, and a changing economy will require strong leadership and bold solutions.
But nor should the enormity of our collective challenges inspire haste.

The government should continue to investigate transformative projects like high-speed rail, and value-capture should play a role. But it should be used to support necessary infrastructure rather than land speculation.

Instead, we should look to invest in solutions that bring people together rather than spread them apart, and plan for innovation rather than betting big on one technology. Instead of reinventing our cities, lets keep building on what already makes them great.
